content.description: Short route of about 3 real moves. Fairly dirty foot holds. Start in the water, pull in the crack, mantel the starting ledge, then make your way up the flake.
content.location: On a 20 ft boulder just north of Frye's Leap. Obvious flake dead center of the boulder.

content.description: Use the undercling to pull up out of the water and follow the cracks along to the top out.
content.location: Right in front of Frye's Leap. Only really a climb past September.

content.description: Pull up on the far right near the small pine and step up to the undercling. There are three small chips for feet. Slide left and reach up to the textured part of the rock for some slopey crimps. Step out left to a smear and then pull up onto the sloper top and mantel out. This last move is a little dangerous because the feet are smeared and the rock is a little crumbley. I gave myself a good smoke in the chin here on my second ascent.
content.location: Around the far right side of Frye's leap.

content.description: Up on the left between the two boulders, across the ledge, swing out on the scab and then pull up and top out.

Start at the crack on the right, stay on the front slab. Two crimps that transition into a mantel for the top out are a little dicey so the grade is higher. Careful not to fall here as the slight runout would make for a pretty unfun fall. As with all of these climbs, they would be pretty short at the begining of the season. Better climbed after August.
content.location: The slab immediately to the right of Samuel Drinkwater's Galley Hole.

content.description: Two lines up this boulder, both roughly the same grade. These will inevitably be better later in the season, ideally after September, when there is more to climb. See image for lines. A couple really cool moves here on both of these. The rock is rough. Don't slip!
content.location: To the immediate left of Frye's Leap. Right in front of the big slab.

content.description: Use the dark hole as a start and top out.
content.location: Look for the hole, it's right of Sarah's Pencil

content.description: Frye's Leap is known around the lake as a cliff jumping spot. The large rock faces and deep water make for potentially decent deep water soloing. This isn't Spain, but there appeared to be several potential lines.
